      <h2>Complete Guide to Electrical Repairs in West Michigan</h2>
      <p>
        Electrical repair work covers everything from a flickering light fixture to a panel that's actively smoking. The
        hardest part for most homeowners isn't the fix — it's knowing what's an inconvenience worth scheduling next week
        versus a real safety issue that warrants a same-day call. This guide breaks down the warning signs and what each
        of them usually means in West Michigan homes.
      </p>

      <h3>Emergency vs Same-Day vs Whenever</h3>
      <p>Three triage categories cover almost every call we get:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Emergency (turn off main, call now):</strong> active smoke, visible flames or glowing inside an outlet
          or panel, repeated sparking, or a burning smell that intensifies after you turn off the breaker. See
          <a href="/blog/burning-smell-from-outlet">burning smell from an outlet: what to do in the next 5 minutes</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Same-day:</strong> whole-house flickering that's getting worse, a burning smell that fades when you unplug
          a specific appliance, brightening on one side of the house while dimming on the other (failing utility neutral),
          or a breaker that won't reset. See
          <a href="/blog/flickering-lights-when-to-worry">flickering lights: when it's annoying vs an emergency</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>This week:</strong> a single breaker that trips occasionally, one outlet that feels warm but works, a fixture
          that flickers only with certain bulbs (dimmer compatibility), or AFCI breakers tripping on motor loads (vacuum,
          treadmill). See
          <a href="/blog/why-breakers-trip">why does my breaker keep tripping?</a>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>What an Electrician Actually Checks</h3>
      <p>A diagnostic visit covers four standard measurements:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Voltage on both legs at the panel.</strong> Confirms utility-side balance. Severe imbalance signals a failing
          utility neutral.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Voltage stability under load.</strong> Major appliances on and off, watching for sag or surge.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>IR thermography on suspect connections.</strong> Hot spots in the panel are loose connections; they fail
          catastrophically eventually.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Receptacle and circuit verification.</strong> Tester at representative outlets confirms grounding, polarity,
          and wiring integrity.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3>The Most Common Issues We See</h3>
      <p>
        Across hundreds of West Michigan service calls, the same handful of root causes accounts for the majority of
        diagnostic work:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Backstabbed connections.</strong> Cheap receptacles use spring-clip terminals on the back that loosen over
          time. Arcing causes burning smell, flickering, and eventually outlet failure. The fix is re-terminating to side
          screws or replacing with a quality device.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Overloaded circuits.</strong> Adding window AC, space heaters, or kitchen appliances to circuits not sized
          for the load. Common in older homes that haven't seen circuit re-balancing in decades.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Aluminum branch wiring.</strong> Common in 1965–1973 homes. Connections at receptacles and switches loosen,
          corrode, and overheat. See
          <a href="/blog/aluminum-wiring-what-to-do">aluminum wiring: what to do if you have it</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Federal Pacific and Zinsco panels.</strong> Documented failure-to-trip risk. Replace regardless of condition.
          See <a href="/blog/zinsco-fpe-panel-replacement">why Zinsco and Federal Pacific panels need to go</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Failing utility neutral.</strong> The most dangerous diagnostic finding. Causes one leg to drift high while
          the other drops, frying electronics and creating fire risk. Call the utility's emergency line first; we confirm
          with leg-to-neutral measurements.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Knob-and-tube wiring on overloaded circuits.</strong> Vintage wiring designed for 1920s loads is handling
          modern appliances. See
          <a href="/blog/knob-and-tube-wiring-what-to-do">knob-and-tube wiring: what to do if you still have it</a>.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>AFCI, GFCI, and Code-Driven Repairs</h3>
      <p>
        Modern code requires <a href="/glossary/afci">AFCI</a> protection in most living spaces and
        <a href="/glossary/gfci">GFCI</a> protection in any wet location.
        <a href="/glossary/nec-210-12">NEC 210.12</a> details the AFCI requirement. Repairs that open walls, add circuits,
        or extend existing circuits typically require bringing affected portions up to current code. See
        <a href="/blog/gfci-vs-afci-vs-dual-function">GFCI vs AFCI vs dual-function breakers</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>When a Repair Becomes a Bigger Project</h3>
      <p>
        Some repairs reveal underlying scope that's worth addressing while the panel or wall is open. The most common
        scope expansions:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          A failing panel turns into a <a href="/panel-upgrades">panel upgrade</a> when the bus or breakers can't be safely
          repaired piecemeal.
        </li>
        <li>
          Aluminum wiring on multiple circuits turns into a <a href="/code-corrections">code-correction project</a> or insurance-required
          remediation.
        </li>
        <li>
          Repeated outages in lakeshore communities turn into a <a href="/generators">generator install</a>
          conversation.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        We always flag this during the diagnostic — you get a same-day repair quote plus an honest read on whether the
        bigger scope is worth doing now versus later.
      </p>
